##When my mother was a doctor in Hubei Province, I sent her a mask from America

Micro-signal Zairenjian11

Features, with a calm narrative against the cold | phoenix network produced in the human studio

Phoenix News Client, produced by Phoenix Network Studio on Earth

My mother was a doctor at Xiangyang Central Hospital in Xiangyang, Hubei Province. As of February 17,1,155 cases of new crown pneumonia had been confirmed in Xiangyang since the outbreak began, making it the seventh largest city in Hubei Province.

I live in Washington, USA.

On January 21, I called my mother, thinking of the sporadic reports of the Hubei epidemic at that time, asked casually, "how is home? ". "It's serious! " She said in a low voice. "Many haven't been diagnosed yet, but we all know that at the hospital. "

I asked her if she had enough protection, and she said she had enough, so I didn't have to worry. Hang up the phone, I also feel that they worry too much, the hospital is the most medical supplies, from the home of cotton swab, alcohol, cotton what is more than used up.

Thinking of a business trip to San Francisco in two weeks, I opened Amazon and prepared to buy a bag of face masks for my own use. Surprisingly, several vendors are showing shortages. When you buy a mask, you also get a recommendation for a protective medical suit. I laughed and took a screenshot of my friend's message saying, is this a robbery gone wrong?

Overnight, reports of the Wuhan outbreak suddenly increased. Wuhan was sealed off on January 23.

Early on the morning of the 24th, I saw my mother sending me a message on Wechat, hoping I'd better buy an N95 mask in America and mail it back.

I quickly got out of bed and turned on the computer.

I did not expect Amazon mask all sold out, the earliest shipment will not wait until after February. The door of the pharmacy can not buy, the clerk told me that the online display is not much stock.

I remember two days ago my colleague mentioned home improvement and Building Materials Store Home Depot and The mask, immediately open The website. Yes, he still has it in stock, you can pick it up at the store or mail it. I ordered eight boxes. In order to get the goods more quickly, I choose to pick them up at the store.

I rescheduled the whole meeting and told my colleagues that there was an epidemic in my hometown in Hubei, China, and I was in a hurry to buy a mask. I drove 45 minutes to the Home Depot to pick up the goods. I actually have a home depot closer by, but this is the only one that has them in stock. Before checkout, wechat suddenly flooded with articles asking for social support from Hubei hospitals, including MOM's hospital. I felt so bad that I bought four more boxes and nearly emptied the store.

When I checked out, the clerk asked me, are you going to China on business, and I said no, my family is in China, and I wanted to send the mask back. "Is your family from Wuhan? Hubei? " She asked. I said yes.

I have lived in the United States for several years, and every time a foreigner asks me where I am from in China and I say Hubei, they ask is this place near Beijing or Shanghai? I mean, it's not even close. It's in the middle. They were so confused, they stopped asking. Now, even the building materials store cashier can accurately pronounce the name of home, but because of the epidemic, I mixed feelings.

Masks in the trunk.

After loading the masks into the trunk, I hurried to the post office. I have a friend whose mother recently returned from California, and I heard that an overseas donor channel has been opened, and San Jose, California, is a collection point. I'M GONNA send my mask to California, and I hope my friend's mom brings as many as she can, but if she can't, she'll donate it all to San Jose.

The evening is New Year's Eve, I call Home New Year. Mom and dad happened to be in Grandma's house, although they are indoors, but also wearing gas mask-like masks, in case there is any virus, will infect the elderly. I know it's scientific, but it's still sad to see them in the video with their masks on. I told them I bought 300 masks and sent them to California. Mom was thrilled.

She's the head of the department. She said there'd be so many masks she could give to all the other doctors. She also says she goes to the clinic after the Spring Festival, and her outpatient room is on the same floor as the smoking section. But resources are tight right now, and only the respiratory and infection doctors have protective clothing and goggles. They don't have one in general. We'll have to keep an eye on them.

Screenshots with MOM and Dad.

I remembered the mugging suit I'd given my friend a few days earlier, and immediately switched back on Amazon. The store I was looking at is gone. I found one in stock, but this one doesn't have a hat. It's off the shelf. I couldn't care less, so I ordered some goggles.

It's too late to ask the classmate's mother for help. I need to send it back to China by express. In all these years, I've never sent an international express. I have always felt that both countries are rich in goods and there is no need to send anything to each other. I have two days to find out how the United States to China Express, after entering the mainland how to transshipment.

Saturday was the first day of the New Year, and I had lunch with my roommate from Shiyan, Hubei Province, at Mama Chang's. Mama Chang is a well-known Hubei restaurant in the greater Washington area, owned by a Huanggang man who previously worked as a chef at the Chinese embassy. We ordered Wuhan Three fresh bean skin. It is one of the most common dishes ordered by my roommate and I, but when I ordered again, my heart was in my hometown and I felt a lot of emotion.

■ A half-eaten skin of three fresh beans.

Roommate's worried about Shiyan's family, and he wants to send some masks home. I made inquiries at Fedex, UPS and DHL. We decided to share a box and send medical supplies to a friend's home in Beijing on Monday, who then split them into two express deliveries to Xiangyang and Shiyan, using SF express to go.

On Monday, the 27th, early in the morning, roommate took the package to the Fedex store. Soon she called me to say that the charge was much higher than the previous inquiry, and that a small box to fly to Beijing would cost more than four hundred and sixty bucks. It took us about two seconds to reach an agreement: no matter how expensive it was, if we sent the goods one day earlier, it would arrive in Beijing one day earlier, and there would be no time to compare prices with other places. Roommate quickly paid the freight, and we split it 50-50.

■ I prepared supplies for my family, with the abbreviation of city written on the small package for my friends in Beijing to separate them. This is the most expensive delivery I've ever made.

In the evening, I called my mother again and told her that both supplies had been sent. She was so happy that her eyes cracked into a smile as she skyped with her, looking forward to the future.

The delivery was slower than expected. The boxes, sent on January 27th, did not arrive on February 7th: It took three days to clear through customs, the 3rd was over, and every day since then has been a failure to deliver, and the dates have been pushed back day by day. Fedex called to say it was short-staffed because of a major shutdown, and that it should be open for business after Feb. 8, with the hope that it could be delivered later.

Another box, sent to California, was brought home by a friend's mother. They were in Liaoning and needed to be fedexed back to Hubei, and in early February they also ran into a sudden suspension of domestic deliveries. Family Members of Friends Inquire about SF express and China Post every day, hoping to post them as soon as they are open for business.

■ The protective gear I bought.

All I can do now is try to call home as often as I can. Every day my parents tell me what new dance I have learned from the video today and what new play I will be watching tomorrow.

Mom Corey had several doctors pulled out to help in the suction department, but she didn't have many patients of her own because no one dared come to the hospital.

These days, I received a lot of friends, students of the message, ask me about home, my mother how. I know it's supposed to be serious, but every time I see mom and dad in the video, they're happy, like they're not at the center of the epidemic, and the lockdown never happened to them.

■ All the deliveries have been delivered these days, and mom has already put them on to go to work.

Now, every day I open a social networking site, and it's all about what's going on. I only hope that our fellow countrymen in Hubei can get through this crisis as soon as possible.
